#Use logical operator to test if a number is both greater than 10 and even
a <- 34
b <- 9
(a<10) & (b>10)

#What is the Difference between & and && ??
&: (Name) Vectorized AND, (Type) Element Wise, (Works on) Vectors, (Purpose) Compares each element of two Logical vectors.
When to use: Working with vectors or data frames (row-wise comparisons).
&&: (Name) Short Circuit AND, (Type) Single, (Works on) Single Values only, (Purpose) Compares only the first element of each logical vector.
When to use: Logical tests in if, while, or ifelse conditions.

x <- c(TRUE, FALSE, TRUE)
y <- C(TRUE, TRUE, FALSE)
x&y
#O/P: TRUE, FALSE, FALSE
Explaination : True & True gives me True, False and True gives me False, True and False gives me False.

x&&y
#O/P: TRUE
Explaination : It only checks the first element of each vector (x[1] and y[1]) → TRUE & TRUE → TRUE.
It ignores the rest.

#Example of wrong v/s right use
x <- c(TRUE, FALSE, TRUE)
#Wrong: gives warning or unwanted behavior
if (x & TRUE) print("Yes")
#Correct:
if (x && TRUE) print("Yes")
Because IF() expects a single TRUE/FALSE, not a vector

